04149nam a22005655i 9780776619989DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807766199897 a10.1515/97807766199892doi  a(DE-B1597)668192  a(OCoLC)824081688  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB2430.F724bF54 2012eb 7aPOL0420002bisacsh04a1942231 aFillion, Réal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFoucault and the Indefinite Work of Freedom /cRéal Fillion. 1aOttawa : bUniversity of Ottawa Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (478 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhilosophica00tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction. Making Sense of History Making Sense of Us -- tI Foucault and the Idea of History -- tII History Considered Generally: Thinking Freedom through Domination -- tIII Foucault after Hyppolite: Toward an A-Theistic Theodicy -- tIV Madness and the Cunning of Reason -- tV A Contrastive History of Punitive Reason -- tVI From History as Self-Awareness to Self-Wariness through History -- tConclusion: The Indefinite and Undefined Work of Freedom as History -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis work underscores the need to examine history philosophically, not only to better appreciate how it unfolds and relates to our own unfolding lives, but to better appreciate our free engagement in this changing world. Linking a conception of ourselves as free beings to the historical process was of central importance to the classical speculative philosophies of history of the nineteenth century, most notably Hegel’s. Michel Foucault’s work is often taken to be the antithesis of this kind of speculative approach. This book argues that Foucault, on the contrary, like Hegel, sees freedom as tied to the self-movement of thought as it realizes and shapes the world. Unlike Hegel, however, he does not see in that self-movement the process of Spirit reconciling itself with the world and thereby realizing itself as freedom. Rather, he sees in the freedom at the core of the self-movement of thought a possible threat around which that movement consolidates itself and gives shape to the world. Foucault’s work is therefore not a simple rejection of Hegel’s speculative philosophy of history, but rather an inversion of the manner in which history and freedom are related: for Hegel history realizes or actualizes the “idea” of freedom, whereas for Foucault freedom realizes or actualizes the “materiality” of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComputer software -- Reliability. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aLibertyxPhilosophy. 0aSystems software. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780776619989?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780776619989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780776619989/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles